In LaTeX, you can generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically using the `\tableofcontents` command and the `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc. commands. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Some text in the introduction.

\subsection{Background}
\label{sec:intro:bg}

More text in the background section.

\subsubsection{Previous Work}
\label{sec:intro:bg:prev}

Even more text in the previous work subsection.

\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}

Text about the methods used.

\subsection{Data Collection}
\label{sec:methods:data}

Text about data collection.

\subsubsection{Data Analysis}
\label{sec:methods:analysis}

Text about data analysis.

\end{document}
```

In this example:

1. The `\documentclass{article}` command specifies the document class (in this case, an article).
2. The `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}` commands delimit the document body.
3. The `\tableofcontents` command generates the TOC.
4. The `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` commands define the headings and labels for the sections, subsections, and subsubsections, respectively. The `\label` command assigns a unique label to each section, which is used to reference it in the TOC.

When you compile this LaTeX document, the TOC will be generated automatically, listing the sections, subsections, and subsubsections with their corresponding page numbers. The TOC will look something like this:

```
Contents
----------------

1 Introduction ....................................................... 1
   1.1 Background ................................................... 1
      1.1.1 Previous Work ........................................ 1
2 Methods ........................................................... 2
   2.1 Data Collection ............................................ 2
      2.1.1 Data Analysis ........................................ 3
```

Note that the actual formatting and layout of the TOC may vary depending on the document class and any customizations you make to the LaTeX document.

